 SKUKUZA – The South African National Parks (SANParks) announced the arrest of three field rangers on Wednesday January 16. According to a statement by the communications and marketing department o the Kruger National Park (KNP), they were arrested on suspicion of poaching in the KNP. The suspects were based at Crocodile Bridge Section and are currently in custody for further investigation until they appear in court. “It is always very sad when your own staff become involved in poaching, however I want to congratulate the SANParks and SAPS investigators for their diligent work in bringing these members to book”, commented KNP managing executive, Glenn Phillips. “Slowly but surely we are coming to grips with people within our ranks who are sabotaging our efforts in this campaign. “We still have confidence in those who are committed and loyal and would like to encourage them to continue with the excellent work. We will not be deterred in ensuring that we are successful in continuing the fight against the scourge of wildlife crime in KNP.” The arrests were a joint effort by the SANParks rangers, Environmental Investigation Unit, SAPS and Directorate for Priority Crime Investigation. 